<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <title>Model Info</title>
  <%- include('partials/head') %>
</head>
<body class="min-h-screen flex flex-col">
  <%- include('partials/header') %>

  <main class="flex-1 max-w-4xl w-full mx-auto px-6 py-8 space-y-6">

    <div class="card bg-white shadow-xl border-t-4 border-[var(--maroon)]">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h2 class="card-title text-[var(--navy)] border-l-4 border-[var(--maroon)] pl-3">
          About This Project
        </h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mt-2">
          This web application demonstrates the <strong>CSM3601 - Heart Disease Prediction</strong>
          machine learning project. It uses the UCI Cleveland Heart Disease dataset (303 patients,
          13 clinical features) and the same data cleaning, outlier-capping, one-hot encoding,
          Min-Max scaling, and feature selection (SelectKBest) pipeline developed in Phase 2 (EDA &amp;
          Data Preparation) of the project.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mt-2">
          Three classification algorithms were trained and compared: <strong>Logistic Regression</strong>,
          <strong>Random Forest</strong>, and <strong>Decision Tree</strong>, using a stratified
          80/20 train-test split and 5-fold cross-validation. <strong>Random Forest was selected as the deployed model</strong> because it achieved
          the highest ROC-AUC score of <strong>0.96</strong> and the highest test accuracy of
          <strong>88.52%</strong> among all three models. Random Forest also demonstrated superior
          precision (88.89%), meaning it produces fewer false positives — a critical quality for
          medical screening tools where incorrectly flagging a healthy patient as high-risk causes
          unnecessary anxiety and follow-up costs. As an ensemble of 100 decision trees, it is
          inherently more robust to overfitting than a single Decision Tree, and more capable of
          capturing non-linear feature interactions than Logistic Regression, which assumes a
          linear relationship between features and the log-odds of heart disease.
        </p>
        <% if (selectedFeatures && selectedFeatures.length) { %>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mt-2">
            Top features selected by SelectKBest and used by the deployed model:
            <span class="font-mono text-sm"><%= selectedFeatures.join(', ') %></span>
          </p>
        <% } %>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card bg-white shadow-xl border-t-4 border-[var(--navy)]">
      <div class="card-body">
        <h2 class="card-title text-[var(--navy)] border-l-4 border-[var(--maroon)] pl-3">
          Model Comparison Results
          <span class="badge text-white ml-2" style="background-color: var(--navy);">Deployed: <%= modelName %></span>
        </h2>

        <% if (metrics && metrics.length) { %>
          <div class="overflow-x-auto mt-3">
            <table class="table">
              <thead>
                <tr class="text-white" style="background-color: var(--navy);">
                  <th>Model</th>
                  <th>CV Accuracy</th>
                  <th>Test Accuracy</th>
                  <th>Precision</th>
                  <th>Recall</th>
                  <th>F1-score</th>
                  <th>ROC-AUC</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <% metrics.forEach(function(row) { %>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="font-semibold"><%= row.model %></td>
                    <td><%= row.cv_accuracy %></td>
                    <td><%= row.test_accuracy %></td>
                    <td><%= row.precision %></td>
                    <td><%= row.recall %></td>
                    <td><%= row.f1_score %></td>
                    <td><%= row.roc_auc %></td>
                  </tr>
                <% }) %>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        <% } else { %>
          <div role="alert" class="alert alert-warning mt-2">
            <span>No metrics available yet — run <code>python train_model.py</code> first.</span>
          </div>
        <% } %>
      </div>
    </div>

  </main>

  <%- include('partials/footer') %>
</body>
</html>
